WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.320
Hello, in this video I'm going to be talking about updates to webR's developer API in webR 0.2.0.

00:00:11.920 --> 00:00:16.000
So I want to jump straight in there and talk about some performance improvements that we've made

00:00:16.639 --> 00:00:22.719
while using webR with other JavaScript frameworks. So it is possible to work entirely within webR

00:00:22.719 --> 00:00:28.240
and return images directly from webR's graphics devices, but you might want to also integrate

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:35.200
webR into external JavaScript frameworks, including visualization packages. So there's

00:00:35.200 --> 00:00:39.840
an example sort of workflow shown on the screen there that you might want to do. So you would,

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:45.919
after initializing webR, you can imagine that you have some JavaScript data and you want to get that

00:00:45.919 --> 00:00:52.720
data into R so we can process it in some way. So webR has APIs to do that. Here, for example,

00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:59.919
that JavaScript data is being bound to a variable in the global environment in the running R process.

00:01:01.520 --> 00:01:05.199
Once that's been done and that data is transferred to the R worker thread,

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:12.800
you can evaluate some R code. Here, just the function doAnalysis is being evaluated,

00:01:12.800 --> 00:01:16.800
but this could really be anything in R. This could be something quite complicated,

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:22.800
such as some kind of complicated data manipulation with the plier or some kind of

00:01:22.800 --> 00:01:30.400
sophisticated statistical analysis with tidy models. In any case, once you've done that

00:01:31.599 --> 00:01:38.800
computation, an R object will be returned to you and then you can convert that R object

00:01:38.800 --> 00:01:45.040
back into the JavaScript environment with this toJs method. That data is transferred from the R

00:01:45.040 --> 00:01:50.800
worker environment back to the JavaScript environment where you can use it in some way.

00:01:52.320 --> 00:01:58.080
So if this is the kind of workflow that as a webR developer you'd be interested in,

00:01:59.120 --> 00:02:05.199
what we want to do is make sure that transferring of data from the JavaScript environment into R

00:02:05.760 --> 00:02:10.800
and back out of R into the JavaScript environment is as efficient and performant as possible.

00:02:11.520 --> 00:02:19.199
We've made some changes in webR 0.2.0 to support that. That transfer was originally done by

00:02:19.199 --> 00:02:25.839
encoding the data in a format called JSON. That's been replaced with something called the Message

00:02:25.839 --> 00:02:33.039
Pack protocol, which is binary-based instead of text-based and more efficient in other ways.

00:02:33.600 --> 00:02:38.160
Initial testing shows an order of magnitude performance improvement with this change,

00:02:38.160 --> 00:02:45.279
so it was well worth looking into, especially when working with large sets of JavaScript data.

00:02:48.320 --> 00:02:54.880
If you are working in this way, an example now is shown on the screen of what you can do by

00:02:54.880 --> 00:03:01.759
moving data in and out of the R environment. Here, the start of this example installs an R

00:03:01.759 --> 00:03:05.679
package just to get some data. It's called the ParmaPenguins package.

00:03:06.960 --> 00:03:12.880
Then the next part of the example is basically just grabbing that data. So here we're evaluating

00:03:12.880 --> 00:03:18.639
some R code, but really we're just returning the Penguins data object. That's being converted into

00:03:18.639 --> 00:03:24.240
JavaScript and then transferred into a slightly different format. There's no real computational

00:03:24.240 --> 00:03:30.639
happening here on lines 8 to 16. It's just changing the shape of the data to better match

00:03:31.839 --> 00:03:37.360
data that is understood by the observable visualization framework, a JavaScript framework.

00:03:38.479 --> 00:03:42.880
If you have used observable before, you probably recognize these next lines. They should be fairly

00:03:42.880 --> 00:03:54.080
familiar. They're the standard way to draw a dot plot in observable. That can now take that data

00:03:54.080 --> 00:04:00.240
that came from R that could have been modified and computed on in a sophisticated way,

00:04:01.199 --> 00:04:06.960
and then plotted in the JavaScript native environment. When you do that, this is what

00:04:06.960 --> 00:04:12.960
you get. A plot that looks like this, produced by observable, but with the data itself coming from

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:19.119
R. I like this example because it demonstrates one of the real benefits to web technologies

00:04:19.119 --> 00:04:24.640
in general, which is interconnectivity. It's very easy to flexibly connect different projects

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:29.119
together when you're working on the web. I think this is a good example of that when it comes to

00:04:30.079 --> 00:04:34.000
joining WebR as part of a wider JavaScript project.

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:41.119
Another change we've made is for TypeScript users. When you're working in TypeScript,

00:04:41.119 --> 00:04:45.839
it's really important to pay attention to the types of objects. That's true of objects that

00:04:45.839 --> 00:04:52.160
are coming from R too. In this example, you can see that we're just evaluating this string here,

00:04:52.160 --> 00:04:59.440
which produces an R double object. Then we're running a method toNumber, which exists on a

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:06.320
WebR double object, and just converts that number into a JavaScript number. Converts the double

00:05:06.320 --> 00:05:11.679
into a JavaScript number. This is actually an error under TypeScript. The reasoning for that

00:05:11.679 --> 00:05:18.959
is that evalR, the function that evaluates R code, could evaluate anything. It doesn't have

00:05:18.959 --> 00:05:24.160
to return a double, it could return a character, it could return a logical vector, it could return

00:05:24.160 --> 00:05:32.799
pretty much anything. There's no guarantee that this toNumber method exists in the WebR API to

00:05:32.799 --> 00:05:40.000
be used on this R object. In fact, evalR is just typed to return an R object. That means it really

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:47.200
could be any kind of fundamental R data type. There's a couple of ways to handle this.

00:05:49.119 --> 00:05:55.040
Before current release of WebR, the way we were using was a TypeScript type assertion feature

00:05:55.040 --> 00:06:00.720
using this add keyword. Basically, we just take the result and we say, okay, this object is

00:06:00.720 --> 00:06:06.720
definitely a double. Therefore, TypeScript is able to know that you can use the toNumber method on it,

00:06:06.720 --> 00:06:14.799
which again, exists in the WebR API. That works, but it has a problem. It means that you need to

00:06:14.799 --> 00:06:20.880
know for definite what type of object is returned by evalR. You need to know exactly what R object

00:06:20.880 --> 00:06:26.640
is being returned. Otherwise, this is an assertion, so it could be wrong. I could be returning

00:06:26.640 --> 00:06:32.239
a number here, but setting it as an R character, and that would cause issues further down the line.

00:06:35.040 --> 00:06:40.959
WebR ships with type predicate functions, and here is an example of one of them, isRDouble,

00:06:40.959 --> 00:06:45.040
and similar functions exist for other fundamental R object types, isRCharacter,

00:06:45.040 --> 00:06:53.200
isRLogical. What that allows you to do is create a branch where the type of that object is checked

00:06:53.200 --> 00:07:00.079
by isRDouble. If the R object is a double, that function returns true. Because that function

00:07:00.079 --> 00:07:05.279
returns true only in that case, TypeScript is able to deduce that inside this branch,

00:07:05.279 --> 00:07:12.320
the object variable is definitely an R double, and therefore, it is perfectly fine to use that

00:07:12.320 --> 00:07:19.200
toNumber method that exists on an R double. This is quite nice because it means that you can

00:07:19.200 --> 00:07:23.679
return different types of object with evalR. It doesn't have to just be one particular type of

00:07:23.679 --> 00:07:28.000
R object, and you could have different branches and different if statements to handle different

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:36.480
types of object. The next thing I'd like to talk about is handling errors. One of the issues that

00:07:36.480 --> 00:07:44.399
we had with the previous version of WebR is that if you have some R code that causes an error

00:07:44.399 --> 00:07:52.399
condition, the evalR function automatically converts that into a JavaScript error, which is

00:07:52.399 --> 00:07:56.880
nice because it means that you can handle errors in R code in the native JavaScript environment.

00:07:58.000 --> 00:08:01.440
The issue with that is if you have some kind of code like the following, where you

00:08:02.399 --> 00:08:09.760
evaluate some R code and then do some JavaScript work on the result, and an error is thrown,

00:08:09.760 --> 00:08:14.959
it's not entirely clear where that error came from. It could have come from inside R, or it could

00:08:14.959 --> 00:08:20.480
come from deep inside this JavaScript function. There were ways to handle that. You could

00:08:20.480 --> 00:08:26.959
parse the message to work out exactly what the error means, or you could do other

00:08:26.959 --> 00:08:32.239
things, but they're not particularly elegant. One of the changes we've made is that

00:08:34.000 --> 00:08:41.599
errors from R now are thrown as this WebR error, as an instance of this WebR error class

00:08:42.559 --> 00:08:50.239
that exists in the package. That means that you can check using the instance of

00:08:50.239 --> 00:08:55.840
a keyword in JavaScript to see, is this object a WebR error, or is it just some other JavaScript

00:08:55.840 --> 00:09:01.280
error? Then you can handle that error as you like, based on whether it came from some R code,

00:09:01.280 --> 00:09:07.039
or it came from your JavaScript code. It's just a nice, easy way to be able to check exactly

00:09:07.039 --> 00:09:11.280
where your error condition came from.

00:09:15.599 --> 00:09:22.000
We've made changes to the WebR canvas messaging system. As I said in the first video,

00:09:22.559 --> 00:09:28.880
we've upgraded the WebR canvas to have a lot more support for different features,

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:35.280
including drawing canvas graphics on the worker thread, and then displaying them on the main thread

00:09:35.280 --> 00:09:41.039
in a different way, using off-screen canvas. Due to those changes, we've redesigned the messaging

00:09:41.039 --> 00:09:47.119
system for the canvas device. There are now a few different messages. This message,

00:09:47.119 --> 00:09:52.960
canvas new page, indicates that a new plot has been created. Previously, it was not clear

00:09:54.000 --> 00:09:57.679
when a new plot had been created in WebR when using the canvas graphics device.

00:09:59.039 --> 00:10:04.000
The canvas image event indicates that there's some image data ready to be shown on the main thread.

00:10:04.000 --> 00:10:09.760
The message looks like this, and the image property that's returned in that message

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:16.880
has a JavaScript image bitmap object. That object can be written to a canvas element

00:10:17.760 --> 00:10:24.000
on the main thread. That message will indicate that a plot has been made,

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:26.000
it's finished rendering, and it's ready to be shown.

00:10:29.280 --> 00:10:38.559
Another change we've made is how WebR is terminated. The following example is a useful

00:10:38.559 --> 00:10:43.440
pattern when you're using WebR to be able to continuously handle WebR output. Here, for

00:10:43.440 --> 00:10:51.919
example, the read function is being used to wait for some output from R. If you have some

00:10:51.919 --> 00:10:58.960
long-running computation that will produce output after a while, it will wait for that output. It

00:10:58.960 --> 00:11:05.039
will wait for one of those output messages. Once the message has been received, it will be handled

00:11:05.039 --> 00:11:10.719
in some way. Here, we have a switch statement to handle different types of message. Then,

00:11:10.719 --> 00:11:16.960
once that message has been handled, the loop wraps around, and it waits for the next message.

00:11:16.960 --> 00:11:23.679
This loop is an infinite loop, so it will continue on indefinitely, continuously handling messages

00:11:23.679 --> 00:11:31.119
from WebR. Now, a question arises. It's possible to terminate a WebR session using this close

00:11:31.119 --> 00:11:38.159
function. That will close the worker thread, terminate the thread, and stop any further R

00:11:38.159 --> 00:11:44.239
processing. If you do that, a question comes up of, okay, well, inside the infinite loop,

00:11:44.960 --> 00:11:50.080
how do I know when to stop? That loop will just sit there waiting for a message that may never

00:11:50.080 --> 00:11:56.799
be received or will never be received. As part of the changes in the new version of WebR, when

00:11:56.799 --> 00:12:02.320
WebR is terminated using this close function, a message of type close is emitted. The very last

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:08.000
thing it does is emit a message of a type close. That means you can add just a single case

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:16.400
statement in your switch here to exit your infinitely running loop when that closed

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:21.440
statement is received. That means that once the WebR thread terminates and that message

00:12:21.440 --> 00:12:26.000
is being received, you don't have that function sitting there waiting for a message that will never

00:12:26.719 --> 00:12:31.200
be received. It helps you clean up after yourself when using WebR.

00:12:33.119 --> 00:12:39.359
That's everything I want to talk about in this video. If you are interested in the WebR API,

00:12:39.359 --> 00:12:45.119
the documentation lists a lot more than I could fit in a single video. Do go and read that.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:52.880
You can install WebR from NPM or you can import it from CDN. If you do use WebR in your own

00:12:52.880 --> 00:12:59.280
applications, please do let me know if you have any exciting features to show me. My email is

00:12:59.280 --> 00:13:12.640
just shown on the screen there and I'd love to see what you do with WebR. Thank you.

